<div id="review_1914365796" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1914365796" />
    <a title="Lauren Cecile" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21468256-lauren-cecile"><img alt="Lauren Cecile" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442457152p2/21468256.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1914365796?book_show_action=true">Jun 07, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lauren Cecile" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lauren Cecile" href="/user/show/21468256-lauren-cecile">Lauren Cecile</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1914365796" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8756344485857582964">Great, well-researched book spanning generations and brilliantly showing how a people&apos;s past influences their futures. <br/>This was the first time I read anything that illustrated so vividly how Africans were complicit in the trans-Atlantic slave trade. (I believe that&apos;s part of the reason that the mainstream critics love it.)<br/>I enjoyed the scenes in Africa even more than the scenes in America although the chapters about how the Alabama penal system used wrongfully convicted convicts to work in the c</span>
  <span id="freeText8756344485857582964" style="display:none">Great, well-researched book spanning generations and brilliantly showing how a people's past influences their futures. <br />This was the first time I read anything that illustrated so vividly how Africans were complicit in the trans-Atlantic slave trade. (I believe that's part of the reason that the mainstream critics love it.)<br />I enjoyed the scenes in Africa even more than the scenes in America although the chapters about how the Alabama penal system used wrongfully convicted convicts to work in the coal mines were especially compelling.<br />I wish the author had varied the names of the characters a little more because the cast was already large and the names were so similar that it was difficult to keep up with them. Also as soon as I became emotionally invested in one character, the chapter changed and another character became the focus. <br />It was mildly reminiscent of Twelve Tribes of Hattie except that there was continuity between characters, eras and geographic migrations.<br />After reading this book, there were so many things I wanted to Google about colonialism, post-Civil War slave labor, etc.<br />The last ten percent of the book was a little pedestrian and the ending a little contrived, but I still appreciated the author's effort to make everything come full circle.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8756344485857582964" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


