<div id="review_3239352092" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3239352092" />
    <a title="Elle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70046142-elle"><img alt="Elle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1548160841p2/70046142.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3239352092?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elle" href="/user/show/70046142-elle">Elle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70046142-elle?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3239352092" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16594747609598291332"><i>
  <b>One of my Top 10 Books of 2020!</b>
</i><br/><br/>I don’t know how anyone could finish reading <i>Homegoing</i> and not find themselves changed afterwards. What a triumph of a debut from Yaa Gyasi. If there ever was a work of fiction that would be beneficial for American high school history students to read, this would be it. <br/><br/><i>Homegoing</i> is as expansive as it is devastating. Following one divided family, Gyasi traces the lineage of two half-sisters as they diverge from the Fante &amp; Asante nations to the United States an</span>
  <span id="freeText16594747609598291332" style="display:none"><i>
  <b>One of my Top 10 Books of 2020!</b>
</i><br /><br />I don’t know how anyone could finish reading <i>Homegoing</i> and not find themselves changed afterwards. What a triumph of a debut from Yaa Gyasi. If there ever was a work of fiction that would be beneficial for American high school history students to read, this would be it. <br /><br /><i>Homegoing</i> is as expansive as it is devastating. Following one divided family, Gyasi traces the lineage of two half-sisters as they diverge from the Fante &amp; Asante nations to the United States and modern day Ghana. Every chapter is a new branch of alternating generations, and we get to watch how each new character introduced is shaped by the traumas of their past. Even those that they may have no memory of, their generational pain rippling.<br /><br />Yaa Gyasi does not pull any punches or dull any edges. Her writing is beautiful, but I can’t imagine anyone sitting down and reading this in just one sitting, despite the shorter length. It felt like every chapter was crafted in order to find a different way to break your heart. <br /><br />The parts with the most levity happened when you’re least expecting them. I loved seeing the life and actions of one character mirror another on the other side of the world. They were seeking different types of freedom, for themselves and descendants they may not have even given any thought to yet. If you have yet to read this, prepare for tears, some smiles and a whole lot of tenacity.<br /><br /><i>I’m now even more eager for <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/48570454.Transcendent_Kingdom" title="Transcendent Kingdom by Yaa Gyasi" rel="nofollow noopener">Transcendent Kingdom</a>, coming 9/8/20, in case anyone hasn’t already added it to their TBR.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="16594747609598291332" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


